    "text": "Yes — a moderate one. Across 12 tagged afternoon-caffeine days versus 41 comparison days, your next-day recovery ran about 6 points lower — a medium-confidence link, and \"linked\" is the right word: this is correlation in your own data, not proof. Today fits the shape, if mildly: your recovery score is 63%, just under your 7-day average recovery of 67%, and your HRV is 60 ms, close to your 30-day average of 60.6 ms. Worth noting: espresso afternoons often travel with other things — later bedtimes, busier days — so the coffee may share the blame. The clean experiment: keep the espresso but cap it at lunchtime for a week, and see whether the tagged-day gap closes. If it does, treat that as a useful lever to keep testing rather than proof the coffee was the whole story.",
